			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				     Excuse me for inturrupting what seems to me to be childish whining, but isnt what we're all looking for here a BALANCED game? Where one's ROLEPLAYING tastes are what determines the character selection? Where everyone works together? O.K. then, if the answer to this is yes, what is the deal with Shadow Knight (and from what I hear, other hybrid)classes? I mean really, no one here (except possibly a moron) wants to actually rule EQ as a supreme class. What we DO want to do, is compete FAIRLY. So why have SK's been so severly punished? When I chose my SK, I wanted to be an evil character with both the ability to tank *almost* like a warrior and sling a few *valuable* spells on the side...what did I GET? Nothing really. Don't take me wrong, I LOVE my SK; but plz, plz, PLZ Verant do SOMETHING helpful here. If we are truely supposed to be 75% warrior, 25% necro, the WHY ARN'T we? Take a look, and I mean a SERIOUS look into it. You were the ones capable of making this game function in the first place. Well by doing that, you have taken on the responsibility of making it run RIGHT, and run FAIRLY. We pay to be here, and in some cases, pay for half the product...<BR>
      As far as this thread being left off..postponed, whatever (which is why I am actually posting here)....what's the deal? You want to look into things happening on the game, but alas, you spend what effort doing it? We, the SK communtity, the hybrid classes (and ALL EverQuestors)in general need your attention. You can't just say &quot;oh, I have more important things to do&quot;, or &quot;I'll look in on it, but honestly I won't be paying much attention.&quot; (which is how his statement felt) What is the point of the threads anyways then? What are we supposed to do now? All funnel into someone's idea of important classes? Or are we going to get some REAL help? Not just a few lines of text to passify a few readers, but enough action to passify most players? The way these threads are being treated are an example...
				</font>
			</td>

